Epoch:1 | IDEA | Scientist1:Thought: Current approaches to uncertainty quantification in interactive segmentation often assume static confidence thresholds or rely on post-hoc calibration methods that do not adapt to user intent. Inspired by the limitations highlighted in Papers 1 and 3—particularly the mismatch between model evaluation assumptions and real human behavior—I recognize a critical gap: models are typically evaluated under idealized user interaction patterns, while real users exhibit diverse strategies and expectations. Paper 2’s emphasis on self-consistency as a signal for calibration suggests that internal model agreement can be leveraged to improve confidence estimation. Building on these insights, I propose an approach that shifts from fixed uncertainty representations to dynamic, user-guided prediction sets. Instead of assuming a universal confidence threshold, the system constructs statistically valid prediction manifolds—sets of plausible segmentations—that adapt based on user-specified confidence levels. This integrates conformal prediction principles with interactive feedback loops, enabling users to explore trade-offs between segmentation precision and coverage. Crucially, unlike prior work that measures calibration against majority human labels (problematic when humans disagree), our method acknowledges ambiguity by outputting *sets* of acceptable masks with guaranteed coverage, calibrated to individual user tolerance for error. The innovation lies in combining interactive segmentation with user-controllable statistical guarantees, allowing clinicians or analysts to adjust "how certain" they want the model to be—visually and quantitatively—on demand.

